    <item>
      <title>Germany Job Seeker Visa: My Personal Experience and Everything You Need to Know</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/expat/eu-series-04-job-seeker-visa-germany-en/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 18 Apr 2026 08:00:00 +0100</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/expat/eu-series-04-job-seeker-visa-germany-en/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Germany&amp;rsquo;s Job Seeker Visa: My Personal Experience and Everything You Need to Know&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;germanys-job-seeker-visa-my-personal-experience-and-everything-you-need-to-know&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#germanys-job-seeker-visa-my-personal-experience-and-everything-you-need-to-know&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;I researched it on YouTube, applied, received a response a year later. Here&amp;rsquo;s exactly what happened — and what you should do today.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;One of the most common questions from people in Turkey (and across the world) who want to move to Germany is: &lt;em&gt;&amp;ldquo;How can I go there to find work if I don&amp;rsquo;t already have a job?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Netherlands vs Luxembourg vs Germany: Why I Chose Germany</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/expat/eu-series-03-comparison-why-germany/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 17 Apr 2026 08:00:00 +0100</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/expat/eu-series-03-comparison-why-germany/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Netherlands vs Luxembourg vs Germany: Why I Chose Germany&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;netherlands-vs-luxembourg-vs-germany-why-i-chose-germany&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#netherlands-vs-luxembourg-vs-germany-why-i-chose-germany&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;I researched all three seriously. Here&amp;rsquo;s the side-by-side comparison — and the honest reasons behind my final decision.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Before I moved to Munich, I spent a long time looking at three countries: the Netherlands, Luxembourg, and Germany. I had job interviews in all three. I received sponsorship offers. I ran the numbers.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Working and Living in Luxembourg: Europe&#39;s Best Kept Secret?</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/expat/eu-series-02-luxembourg/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 16 Apr 2026 08:00:00 +0100</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/expat/eu-series-02-luxembourg/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Working &amp;amp; Living in Luxembourg: Europe&amp;rsquo;s Best Kept Secret?&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;working--living-in-luxembourg-europes-best-kept-secret&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#working--living-in-luxembourg-europes-best-kept-secret&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Free public transport. Low taxes. A country where half the population are immigrants. Here&amp;rsquo;s the full picture.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Luxembourg doesn&amp;rsquo;t come up often in conversations about where to move in Europe. It should.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I had a job interview there. I researched the country seriously. And while I ultimately chose Germany, what I found in Luxembourg surprised me — both the advantages and the very real challenges.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Working and Living in the Netherlands: What I Learned Before Moving</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/expat/eu-series-01-netherlands/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 15 Apr 2026 08:00:00 +0100</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/expat/eu-series-01-netherlands/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Working &amp;amp; Living in the Netherlands: What I Learned Before Moving&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;working--living-in-the-netherlands-what-i-learned-before-moving&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#working--living-in-the-netherlands-what-i-learned-before-moving&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;I applied for jobs there, got a sponsorship offer, and researched everything. Here&amp;rsquo;s what nobody tells you.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The Netherlands was my first serious target when I decided to move abroad. I spent months researching, applied to companies, and got far enough in the process to receive a sponsorship offer. I didn&amp;rsquo;t end up moving there — but I learned an enormous amount along the way.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Quality of Life and Happiness: The Final Verdict</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/living/quality-of-life-final-verdict/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 14 Apr 2026 08:00:00 +0100</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/living/quality-of-life-final-verdict/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Quality of Life &amp;amp; Happiness: The Final Verdict&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;quality-of-life--happiness-the-final-verdict&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#quality-of-life--happiness-the-final-verdict&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;After everything — is Germany better? The honest answer is more complicated than yes or no.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;This is the closing article in the &lt;a href=&#34;&#34; &gt;Turkey vs Germany&lt;/a&gt; series. If you&amp;rsquo;ve read the others, you&amp;rsquo;ll know I&amp;rsquo;ve tried to be honest about both sides throughout. This is where I pull it all together.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Work Life and Work-Life Balance: Turkey vs Germany</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/living/work-life-turkey-vs-germany/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 09 Apr 2026 08:00:00 +0100</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/living/work-life-turkey-vs-germany/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Work Life &amp;amp; Work-Life Balance: Turkey vs Germany&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;work-life--work-life-balance-turkey-vs-germany&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#work-life--work-life-balance-turkey-vs-germany&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;In Turkey, you work hard and stay late. In Germany, you leave on time — and nobody apologises for it.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h2 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;🇹🇷 Turkey: Hustle Culture with Heart&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;-turkey-hustle-culture-with-heart&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#-turkey-hustle-culture-with-heart&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Turkish work culture is intense. Long hours are common and often expected. Being seen to work hard — staying late, being available, putting in visible effort — carries cultural weight. The boundary between work and personal life is porous.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Elderly Care and Family Structure: Turkey vs Germany</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/living/elderly-care-turkey-vs-germany/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 07 Apr 2026 08:00:00 +0100</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/living/elderly-care-turkey-vs-germany/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Elderly Care &amp;amp; Family Structure: Turkey vs Germany&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;elderly-care--family-structure-turkey-vs-germany&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#elderly-care--family-structure-turkey-vs-germany&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;In Turkey, family takes care of family. In Germany, the state steps in. Neither model is perfect.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h2 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;🇹🇷 Turkey: The Family as Safety Net&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;-turkey-the-family-as-safety-net&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#-turkey-the-family-as-safety-net&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;In Turkish culture, caring for elderly parents is not a policy decision — it&amp;rsquo;s a moral expectation. When parents age, children take responsibility. Grandparents often move in with their children&amp;rsquo;s families, or live very close by. The extended family is the primary support structure.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>The Language Barrier: Turkey vs Germany</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/living/language-barrier-turkey-vs-germany/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 05 Apr 2026 08:00:00 +0100</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/living/language-barrier-turkey-vs-germany/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;The Language Barrier: Turkey vs Germany&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;the-language-barrier-turkey-vs-germany&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#the-language-barrier-turkey-vs-germany&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;You can survive in Munich with English. But surviving and living are different things.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h2 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;🇹🇷 Turkey: Your Language, Your World&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;-turkey-your-language-your-world&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#-turkey-your-language-your-world&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Living in Turkey as a Turkish speaker means the world is fully open to you. Every bureaucratic process, every social interaction, every joke, every piece of paperwork — you navigate it all with complete fluency.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Social Life and Making Friends: Turkey vs Germany</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/living/social-life-turkey-vs-germany/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 04 Apr 2026 08:00:00 +0100</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/living/social-life-turkey-vs-germany/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Social Life &amp;amp; Making Friends: Turkey vs Germany&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;social-life--making-friends-turkey-vs-germany&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#social-life--making-friends-turkey-vs-germany&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;ldquo;Germans are cold.&amp;rdquo; Is it true? It&amp;rsquo;s more complicated than that.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h2 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;🇹🇷 Turkey: Warm, Fast, and Deep&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;-turkey-warm-fast-and-deep&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#-turkey-warm-fast-and-deep&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Turkish social culture is famously warm. Strangers become friends quickly. Hospitality is almost a competitive sport — guests must be fed, tea must be offered, no one leaves without feeling welcomed.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Health System: Turkey vs Germany</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/living/health-system-turkey-vs-germany/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 08:00:00 +0100</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/living/health-system-turkey-vs-germany/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Health System: Turkey vs Germany&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;health-system-turkey-vs-germany&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#health-system-turkey-vs-germany&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;From walking into any hospital to waiting weeks for a specialist — here&amp;rsquo;s what actually changed when I moved&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Healthcare is one of those things you don&amp;rsquo;t think about until you need it. Moving countries means rebuilding your entire relationship with the medical system from scratch — new doctors, new insurance, new language, new rules.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Turkey vs Germany: An Honest Comparison After Making the Move</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/living/turkey-vs-germany/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 30 Mar 2026 08:00:00 +0100</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/living/turkey-vs-germany/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Turkey vs Germany: An Honest Comparison After Making the Move&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;turkey-vs-germany-an-honest-comparison-after-making-the-move&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#turkey-vs-germany-an-honest-comparison-after-making-the-move&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Not a travel guide. Not a rant. Just what I&amp;rsquo;ve actually experienced living in both countries.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I want to be clear upfront: this isn&amp;rsquo;t about which country is &amp;ldquo;better.&amp;rdquo; It&amp;rsquo;s about &lt;strong&gt;what I personally found different, harder, easier, worse, and surprisingly better&lt;/strong&gt; — from both sides. Because Germany has real frustrations too.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Why I Left Turkey: The Decision That Changed Everything</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/living/why-i-moved-countries/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 29 Mar 2026 08:00:00 +0100</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/living/why-i-moved-countries/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Why I Left Turkey: The Decision That Changed Everything&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;why-i-left-turkey-the-decision-that-changed-everything&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#why-i-left-turkey-the-decision-that-changed-everything&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;A personal account of weighing family, freedom, and the future — from someone who actually made the move&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Moving to another country is never just a practical decision. It&amp;rsquo;s emotional, messy, and deeply personal. I&amp;rsquo;ve been asked many times: &lt;em&gt;&amp;ldquo;Why did you leave?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em&gt; This is my honest answer.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Trust as a Way of Life: What Germany Taught Me About Believing in People</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/living/trust-in-germany/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 28 Mar 2026 08:00:00 +0100</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/en/germany/living/trust-in-germany/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Trust as a Way of Life: What Germany Taught Me About Believing in People&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;trust-as-a-way-of-life-what-germany-taught-me-about-believing-in-people&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#trust-as-a-way-of-life-what-germany-taught-me-about-believing-in-people&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Living in Munich as an expat from Turkey — small details that changed how I see society&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Germany surprised me. Not with its punctuality, not with its efficiency — but with something quieter and harder to name: &lt;strong&gt;trust&lt;/strong&gt;. The kind of trust that doesn&amp;rsquo;t ask for proof. The kind that assumes you&amp;rsquo;ll do the right thing, even when no one is watching.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
